{"title_page": "Jo\u00e3o Fernandes (rower)", "text_new": "{{short description|Portuguese rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Jo\u00e3o Fernandes\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Portuguese\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1976|6|21|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Jo\u00e3o Fernandes''' (born 21 June 1976) is a Portuguese [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|men's lightweight coxless four]] event at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fe/joao-fernandes-1.html |title=Jo\u00e3o Fernandes Olympic Results |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernandes,Joao}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Portuguese male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Portugal-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Jo\u00e3o Fernandes\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Portuguese\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1976|6|21|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Jo\u00e3o Fernandes''' (born 21 June 1976) is a Portuguese [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's lightweight coxless four|men's lightweight coxless four]] event at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fe/joao-fernandes-1.html |title=Jo\u00e3o Fernandes Olympic Results |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernandes,Joao}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Portuguese male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Portugal-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Portuguese rower\", overriding Wikidata description \"Portuguese rower\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jo%C3%A3o_Fernandes_(rower)"}
{"title_page": "Carlos Oliveira (rower)", "text_new": "{{short description|Portuguese rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Carlos Oliveira\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Portuguese\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1943|9|12|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Carlos Oliveira''' (born 12 September 1943) is a Portuguese [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double sculls|men's double sculls]] event at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ol/carlos-oliveira-1.html |title=Carlos Oliveira Olympic Results |accessdate=18 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oliveira, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Portuguese male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Portugal-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Carlos Oliveira\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Portuguese\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1943|9|12|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Carlos Oliveira''' (born 12 September 1943) is a Portuguese [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's double sculls|men's double sculls]] event at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ol/carlos-oliveira-1.html |title=Carlos Oliveira Olympic Results |accessdate=18 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oliveira, Carlos}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Portuguese male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Portugal-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Portuguese rower\", overriding Wikidata description \"Portuguese rower\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Oliveira_(rower)"}
{"title_page": "Tales of the Bounty Hunters", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox book\n|name = Tales of the Bounty Hunters\n|image = Talesofthebountyhunters.jpg\n|editor = [[Kevin J. Anderson]]\n|author = [[Kevin J. Anderson]]<br>[[Dave Wolverton]]<br>[[Kathy Tyers]]<br>[[M. Shayne Bell]]<br>[[Daniel Keys Moran]]\n|cover_artist = [[Stephen Youll]]\n|country = United States\n|language = English\n|series = \n|subject =[[Star Wars]]\n|genre = [[Science fiction]]\n|publisher = [[Bantam Spectra]]\n|release_date = December 3, 1996\n|media_type = [[Paperback]]\n|pages = 400\n|isbn =  0-553-56816-7\n|preceded_by = \n|followed_by = \n}}\n\n'''''Tales of the Bounty Hunters''''' (1996) is an [[anthology]] of [[Short story|short stories]] set in the fictional ''[[Star Wars]]'' universe. It presents the background stories about each [[bounty hunter]] that was seen aboard [[Darth Vader]]'s [[Star Destroyer]] in the film ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]''. It contains the tale of IG-88, Dengar, Bossk, Zuckuss and 4-LOM, and [[Boba Fett]].<ref>http://www.adherents.com/lit/bk_StarWars_Bounty.html</ref>\n\nThe book was edited by [[Kevin J. Anderson]], who conceived the ''Tales'' book series,<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Tales from Jabba's Palace]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/talesfromjabbasp00newy/page/ ii]|editor=[[Kevin J. Anderson]]|publisher=[[Bantam Books]]|year=1995|isbn=0-553-56815-9}}</ref> and wrote one of the stories as well.\n\n== Contents ==\n=== ''Therefore I Am: The Tale of IG-88'' ===\nWritten by the editor, Kevin J. Anderson, the story of assassin android [[List of Star Wars characters#I|IG-88]] and his three brothers is told from their perspectives, which are automatically shared with one another. When the Imperial engineers realize the droid is [[Sentience|sentient]], they attempt to shut it down, which triggers a defense mechanism. IG-88 kills everyone in the production plant, and goes on the run in an attempt to free other droids in his product line. Two of the four are dismantled by Boba Fett shortly after [[Darth Vader]] places a bounty on [[Han Solo]]. The original droid is revealed to be uploaded to the [[second Death Star]], where he plays tricks on the [[Palpatine|Emperor]].\n\nThe title is a reference to [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] philosopher's [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes]] \"[[Cogito ergo sum|I think, therefore I am]].\" An IG-88 model whose fate is left unknown is killed by [[Dash Rendar]] in the video game ''[[Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire|Shadows of the Empire]]'' (1996).\n\n=== ''Payback: The Tale of Dengar'' ===\nThe story of [[Dengar]] was written by [[Dave Wolverton]]. He is revealed to have gained his injuries in a hovercar race against Han Solo on their shared home planet of Corellia. Shortly before the events of ''The Empire Strikes Back'',<ref>{{cite book|title=Star Wars: The Essential Reader's Companion|url=https://archive.org/details/starwarsclonewar00_2|url-access=registration|last=Hidalgo|first=Pablo|year=2012}}</ref> Dengar works as an assassin and falls in love with the dancer Manaroo. He pursues Solo to take his revenge, and is captured by the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Empire]] upon [[Hoth]]. Vader lets him live with the understanding that he is to capture Solo and his friends alive. He competes with Boba Fett, who spares no punches, to take his bounty.\n\nWhen Manaroo is taken captive on Cloud City, he shoots stormtroopers to free her. He learns to communicate with her psychically and travels to her homeworld to rescue some of her people from Imperial oppression. On [[Tatooine]], Dengar sees Han Solo frozen in carbonite and considers killing [[Jabba the Hutt]]. Boba Fett deduces his plans, and binds him to the desert floor, where he witnesses the ''Millennium Falcon'' depart. Reaching out with his feelings, he is able to contact Manaroo, who comes to free him. Together, they save the naked Boba Fett, whose armor was destroyed by a thermal detonator he used to free himself from the [[sarlacc]].\n\n=== ''The Prize Pelt: The Tale of Bossk'' ===\nThe story of [[List of Star Wars characters#B|Bossk]]\" is told by [[Kathy Tyers]]. Through the perspective of human female Tinian and her [[Wookiee]] mentor Chen, who join Bossk in a hunt for [[Chewbacca]], who is attempting to capture the bounty on Han Solo. Bossk attempts to double-cross his companions, who use a thumb-sized robot to subvert his ship's computer.\n\n=== ''Of Possible Futures: The Tale of Zuckuss and 4-LOM'' ===\nThe tale of the duo [[Zuckuss]] and [[List of Star Wars characters#0\u20139|4-LOM]] was written by [[M. Shayne Bell]]. Zuckuss, who is able to intuit possible futures, meditates shortly before the bounty hunter scene in ''The Empire Strikes Back'', and the duo encounters survivors from the Battle of Hoth.\n[[File:Star Wars and the Power of Costume July 2018 28 (Boba Fett's costume, helmet, and jetpack from Episode VI).jpg|thumb|180px|Boba Fett's costume]]\n\n=== ''The Last One Standing: The Tale of Boba Fett'' ===\nThe story of the most famous ''Star Wars'' bounty hunter, [[Boba Fett]], is told by [[Daniel Keys Moran]]. A prologue set 15 years before ''The Empire Strikes Back'' explores Fett's history with [[Han Solo]]. Then, just before the events of ''Empire'', Fett tracks Solo to the Rebel base on [[Hoth]] to obtain the bounty from [[Jabba the Hutt]], encountering his previous employer [[Darth Vader]]. On [[Tatooine]], Jabba sends the enslaved [[Princess Leia]] to Fett's quarters, where they converse platonically. The majority of the story takes place 15 years after ''Return of the Jedi'', when Fett fell into the [[Sarlacc]];<ref>{{cite book|title=Star Wars: The Essential Reader's Companion|last=Hidalgo|first=Pablo|publisher=Del Rey|date=October 2, 2012|isbn=9780345511195}}</ref> his escape was dealt with in [[Tales from Jabba's Palace#A Barve Like That: The Tale of Boba Fett|another short story by the author]] subtitled ''The Tale of Boba Fett''. Finally, the older Fett takes one last bounty hunting job to pay for his retirement, and encounters his former nemesis Han Solo. The story ends in a [[cliffhanger]] of Fett and Solo in a standoff, with rifles pointed at each other.\n\nA backstory is given for Fett as lawman Jaster Mereel, though this was superseded by the plot of ''[[Star Wars: Episode II \u2013 Attack of the Clones|Attack of the Clones]]'' (2002). The comic ''[[Jango Fett: Open Seasons]]'' [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] Mereel as the mentor of Boba's father, and only a name used by Boba as an alias.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jango Fett: Open Seasons|last=Blackman|first=Haden|publisher=Dark Horse Comics|year=2002}}</ref> The author stated in mid-2018 that [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|Disney]] and [[Lucasfilm]] had considered adapting his story into a [[List of Star Wars films and television series#Unproduced films|standalone movie]], but didn't know how the project was faring after the poor financial performance of ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]''.<ref name=interview>{{cite web|url=https://starwarsinterviews.com/various/authors/daniel-keys-moran-author/|title=Daniel Keys Moran (Author)|website=Star Wars Interviews|date=July 2018|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/boba-fett-movie-han-solo-alden-ehrenreich/|title=The Boba Fett Movie Could Feature Alden Ehrenreich's Han Solo|date=July 6, 2018|work=Screen Rant|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> In late 2018, it was rumored to have been cancelled, and to have featured the entire lineup of bounty hunters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/10/26/star-wars-producers-halt-boba-fett-film/|title=Star Wars producers halt unannounced Boba Fett standalone film|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|website=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 13, 2018|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Tales from the Mos Eisley Cantina]]''\n* ''[[Tales from Jabba's Palace]]''\n* ''[[Tales from the Empire]]''\n* ''[[Tales from the New Republic]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kevin J. Anderson}}\n\n[[Category:1996 books]]\n[[Category:Science fiction anthologies]]\n[[Category:Star Wars Legends novels]]\n[[Category:Works edited by Kevin J. Anderson]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox book\n|name = Tales of the Bounty Hunters\n|image = Talesofthebountyhunters.jpg\n|editor = [[Kevin J. Anderson]]\n|author = [[Kevin J. Anderson]]<br>[[Dave Wolverton]]<br>[[Kathy Tyers]]<br>[[M. Shayne Bell]]<br>[[Daniel Keys Moran]]\n|cover_artist = [[Stephen Youll]]\n|country = United States\n|language = English\n|series = \n|subject =[[Star Wars]]\n|genre = [[Science fiction]]\n|publisher = [[Bantam Spectra]]\n|release_date = December 3, 1996\n|media_type = [[Paperback]]\n|pages = 400\n|isbn =  0-553-56816-7\n|preceded_by = \n|followed_by = \n}}\n\n'''''Tales of the Bounty Hunters''''' (1996) is an [[anthology]] of [[Short story|short stories]] set in the fictional ''[[Star Wars]]'' universe. It presents the background stories about each [[bounty hunter]] that was seen aboard [[Darth Vader]]'s [[Star Destroyer]] in the film ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]''. It contains the tale of IG-88, Dengar, Bossk, Zuckuss and 4-LOM, and [[Boba Fett]].<ref>http://www.adherents.com/lit/bk_StarWars_Bounty.html</ref>\n\nThe book was edited by [[Kevin J. Anderson]], who conceived the ''Tales'' book series,<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Tales from Jabba's Palace]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/talesfromjabbasp00newy/page/ ii]|editor=[[Kevin J. Anderson]]|publisher=[[Bantam Books]]|year=1995|isbn=0-553-56815-9}}</ref> and wrote one of the stories as well.\n\n== Contents ==\n=== ''Therefore I Am: The Tale of IG-88'' ===\nWritten by the editor, Kevin J. Anderson, the story of assassin android [[List of Star Wars characters#I|IG-88]] and his three brothers is told from their perspectives, which are automatically shared with one another. When the Imperial engineers realize the droid is [[Sentience|sentient]], they attempt to shut it down, which triggers a defense mechanism. IG-88 kills everyone in the production plant, and goes on the run in an attempt to free other droids in his product line. Two of the four are dismantled by Boba Fett shortly after [[Darth Vader]] places a bounty on [[Han Solo]]. The original droid is revealed to be uploaded to the second [[Death Star]], where he plays tricks on the [[Palpatine|Emperor]].\n\nThe title is a reference to [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] philosopher's [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes]] \"[[Cogito ergo sum|I think, therefore I am]].\" An IG-88 model whose fate is left unknown is killed by [[Dash Rendar]] in the video game ''[[Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire|Shadows of the Empire]]'' (1996).\n\n=== ''Payback: The Tale of Dengar'' ===\nThe story of [[Dengar]] was written by [[Dave Wolverton]]. He is revealed to have gained his injuries in a hovercar race against Han Solo on their shared home planet of Corellia. Shortly before the events of ''The Empire Strikes Back'',<ref>{{cite book|title=Star Wars: The Essential Reader's Companion|url=https://archive.org/details/starwarsclonewar00_2|url-access=registration|last=Hidalgo|first=Pablo|year=2012}}</ref> Dengar works as an assassin and falls in love with the dancer Manaroo. He pursues Solo to take his revenge, and is captured by the [[Galactic Empire (Star Wars)|Empire]] upon [[Hoth]]. Vader lets him live with the understanding that he is to capture Solo and his friends alive. He competes with Boba Fett, who spares no punches, to take his bounty.\n\nWhen Manaroo is taken captive on Cloud City, he shoots stormtroopers to free her. He learns to communicate with her psychically and travels to her homeworld to rescue some of her people from Imperial oppression. On [[Tatooine]], Dengar sees Han Solo frozen in carbonite and considers killing [[Jabba the Hutt]]. Boba Fett deduces his plans, and binds him to the desert floor, where he witnesses the ''Millennium Falcon'' depart. Reaching out with his feelings, he is able to contact Manaroo, who comes to free him. Together, they save the naked Boba Fett, whose armor was destroyed by a thermal detonator he used to free himself from the [[sarlacc]].\n\n=== ''The Prize Pelt: The Tale of Bossk'' ===\nThe story of [[List of Star Wars characters#B|Bossk]]\" is told by [[Kathy Tyers]]. Through the perspective of human female Tinian and her [[Wookiee]] mentor Chen, who join Bossk in a hunt for [[Chewbacca]], who is attempting to capture the bounty on Han Solo. Bossk attempts to double-cross his companions, who use a thumb-sized robot to subvert his ship's computer.\n\n=== ''Of Possible Futures: The Tale of Zuckuss and 4-LOM'' ===\nThe tale of the duo [[Zuckuss]] and [[List of Star Wars characters#0\u20139|4-LOM]] was written by [[M. Shayne Bell]]. Zuckuss, who is able to intuit possible futures, meditates shortly before the bounty hunter scene in ''The Empire Strikes Back'', and the duo encounters survivors from the Battle of Hoth.\n[[File:Star Wars and the Power of Costume July 2018 28 (Boba Fett's costume, helmet, and jetpack from Episode VI).jpg|thumb|180px|Boba Fett's costume]]\n\n=== ''The Last One Standing: The Tale of Boba Fett'' ===\nThe story of the most famous ''Star Wars'' bounty hunter, [[Boba Fett]], is told by [[Daniel Keys Moran]]. A prologue set 15 years before ''The Empire Strikes Back'' explores Fett's history with [[Han Solo]]. Then, just before the events of ''Empire'', Fett tracks Solo to the Rebel base on [[Hoth]] to obtain the bounty from [[Jabba the Hutt]], encountering his previous employer [[Darth Vader]]. On [[Tatooine]], Jabba sends the enslaved [[Princess Leia]] to Fett's quarters, where they converse platonically. The majority of the story takes place 15 years after ''Return of the Jedi'', when Fett fell into the [[Sarlacc]];<ref>{{cite book|title=Star Wars: The Essential Reader's Companion|last=Hidalgo|first=Pablo|publisher=Del Rey|date=October 2, 2012|isbn=9780345511195}}</ref> his escape was dealt with in [[Tales from Jabba's Palace#A Barve Like That: The Tale of Boba Fett|another short story by the author]] subtitled ''The Tale of Boba Fett''. Finally, the older Fett takes one last bounty hunting job to pay for his retirement, and encounters his former nemesis Han Solo. The story ends in a [[cliffhanger]] of Fett and Solo in a standoff, with rifles pointed at each other.\n\nA backstory is given for Fett as lawman Jaster Mereel, though this was superseded by the plot of ''[[Star Wars: Episode II \u2013 Attack of the Clones|Attack of the Clones]]'' (2002). The comic ''[[Jango Fett: Open Seasons]]'' [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] Mereel as the mentor of Boba's father, and only a name used by Boba as an alias.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jango Fett: Open Seasons|last=Blackman|first=Haden|publisher=Dark Horse Comics|year=2002}}</ref> The author stated in mid-2018 that [[Walt Disney Studios (division)|Disney]] and [[Lucasfilm]] had considered adapting his story into a [[List of Star Wars films and television series#Unproduced films|standalone movie]], but didn't know how the project was faring after the poor financial performance of ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]''.<ref name=interview>{{cite web|url=https://starwarsinterviews.com/various/authors/daniel-keys-moran-author/|title=Daniel Keys Moran (Author)|website=Star Wars Interviews|date=July 2018|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/boba-fett-movie-han-solo-alden-ehrenreich/|title=The Boba Fett Movie Could Feature Alden Ehrenreich's Han Solo|date=July 6, 2018|work=Screen Rant|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> In late 2018, it was rumored to have been cancelled, and to have featured the entire lineup of bounty hunters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2018/10/26/star-wars-producers-halt-boba-fett-film/|title=Star Wars producers halt unannounced Boba Fett standalone film|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|website=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 13, 2018|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Tales from the Mos Eisley Cantina]]''\n* ''[[Tales from Jabba's Palace]]''\n* ''[[Tales from the Empire]]''\n* ''[[Tales from the New Republic]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kevin J. Anderson}}\n\n[[Category:1996 books]]\n[[Category:Science fiction anthologies]]\n[[Category:Star Wars Legends novels]]\n[[Category:Works edited by Kevin J. Anderson]]\n", "name_user": "UpdateNerd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTherefore I Am: The Tale of IG-88:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tales_of_the_Bounty_Hunters"}
