ic Results |accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paula, Jo\u00e3o da}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Portuguese male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Portugal-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Portuguese rower\", overriding Wikidata description \"Portuguese rower\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jo%C3%A3o_da_Paula"}
{"title_page": "Jos\u00e9 Pinheiro (rowing)", "text_new": "{{short description|Portuguese rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Jos\u00e9 Pinheiro\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Portuguese\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1933|3|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Jos\u00e9 Pinheiro''' (born 19 March 1933) is a Portuguese [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's eight|men's eight]] event at the [[1952 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/pi/jose-pinheiro-2.html |title=Jos\u00e9 Pinheiro Olympic Results |accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pinheiro, Jose}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Portuguese male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Portugal-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Jos\u00e9 Pinheiro\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Portuguese\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1933|3|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Jos\u00e9 Pinheiro''' (born 19 March 1933) is a Portuguese [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's eight|men's eight]] event at the [[1952 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/pi/jose-pinheiro-2.html |title=Jos\u00e9 Pinheiro Olympic Results |accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pinheiro, Jose}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Portuguese male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Portugal-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Portuguese rower\", overriding Wikidata description \"Portuguese rower\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Pinheiro_(rowing)"}
{"title_page": "Anthem of the Beiyang Fleet", "text_new": "''Anthem of the Beiyang Fleet''  ({{zh|t=\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u8ecd\u8ecd\u6b4c|s=\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u519b\u519b\u6b4c}}) is the official anthem of [[Beiyang Fleet]], [[Qing Dynasty]]. This anthem was once lost in history, but a scholar called Yue Chen ({{zh|s=\u9648\u60a6}}) re-found this anthem when he went to the United Kingdom in 2012. Then a composer Xue Ye ({{zh|s=\u96ea\u91ce}}) in [[People's Liberation Army]] adapt this anthem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/mil/2014-07/28/c_126805493.htm|title=\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u8ecd\u8ecd\u6b4c\u6d88\u5931120\u5e74\u73fe\u4e16 \u767c\u73fe\u4e8e\u82f1\u570b\u5916\u4ea4\u6a94\u6848|publisher=[[\u83ef\u897f\u90fd\u5e02\u5831]]|date=2014-07-28}}</ref> The documentary ''Rise and Fall of Beiyang Fleet'' presented by CCTV uses this anthem as its [[theme music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jishi.cntv.cn/2014/07/28/ARTI1406536880376615.shtml|title=\u300a\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u519b\u5174\u4ea1\u53f2\u2014\u2014\u7532\u5348\u6d77\u6218120\u5e74\u796d\u300b\u592e\u89c6\u64ad\u51fa|publisher=CCTV|date=2014-07-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713205851/http://jishi.cntv.cn/2014/07/28/ARTI1406536880376615.shtml|archivedate=2017-07-13}}</ref>\n\nThe anthem shares the same tune with [[Tune of Li Zhongtang]].\n\n== Lyrics ==\n===Traditional Chinese===\n\u5bf6\u795a\u5ef6\u5ea5\u842c\u570b\u6b61\n<br>\u666f\u661f\u62f1\u6975\u4e94\u96f2\u7aef\n<br>\u6d77\u6ce2\u6f84\u78a7\u6625\u8f1d\u9e97 \n<br>\u65cc\u7bc0\u82b1\u9593\u96c6\u9cf3\u947e\n\n===Hanyu Pinyin===\nB\u01ceozu\u00f2 y\u00e1nxi\u016b w\u00e0ngu\u00f3 hu\u0101n\n<br>J\u01d0ngx\u012bng g\u01d2ngj\u00ed w\u01d4 y\u00fan du\u0101n\n<br>H\u01ceib\u014d ch\u00e9ngb\u00ec ch\u016bnhu\u012b l\u00ec\n<br>J\u012bngji\u00e9 hu\u0101ji\u0101n j\u00ed f\u00e8nglu\u00e1n\n\n===English Translation===\nTen thousand nations celebrate the [[Dragon Throne|Imperial throne]]'s prosperity\n<br>The fortune star climbs over the iridescent clouds of five colors\n<br>The [[East China Sea|crystal blue ocean]] glitters under spring's sunshine\n<br>Tributaries bow to the [[Emperor of China|Emperor]] like flowers centering a [[Phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]]\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Beiyang Fleet]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links ==\n\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fXpGpgYHj1k ''Anthem of the Beiyang Fleet'' on Youtube]\n\n[[Category:Military history of the Qing dynasty]]\n[[Category:Beiyang Fleet]]\n", "text_old": "''Anthem of the Beiyang Fleet''  ({{zh|t=\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u8ecd\u8ecd\u6b4c|s=\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u519b\u519b\u6b4c}}) is the official anthem of [[Beiyang Fleet]], [[Qing Dynasty]]. This anthem was once lost in history, but a scholar called Yue Chen ({{zh|s=\u9648\u60a6}}) re-found this anthem when he went to the United Kingdom in 2012. Then a composer Xue Ye ({{zh|s=\u96ea\u91ce}}) in [[People's Liberation Army]] adapt this anthem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/mil/2014-07/28/c_126805493.htm|title=\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u8ecd\u8ecd\u6b4c\u6d88\u5931120\u5e74\u73fe\u4e16 \u767c\u73fe\u4e8e\u82f1\u570b\u5916\u4ea4\u6a94\u6848|publisher=[[\u83ef\u897f\u90fd\u5e02\u5831]]|date=2014-07-28}}</ref> The documentary ''Rise and Fall of Beiyang Fleet'' presented by CCTV uses this anthem as its [[theme music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jishi.cntv.cn/2014/07/28/ARTI1406536880376615.shtml|title=\u300a\u5317\u6d0b\u6d77\u519b\u5174\u4ea1\u53f2\u2014\u2014\u7532\u5348\u6d77\u6218120\u5e74\u796d\u300b\u592e\u89c6\u64ad\u51fa|publisher=CCTV|date=2014-07-28|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713205851/http://jishi.cntv.cn/2014/07/28/ARTI1406536880376615.shtml|archivedate=2017-07-13}}</ref>\n\nThe anthem shares the same tune with [[Tune of Li Zhongtang]].\n\n== Lyrics ==\n===Traditional Chinese===\n\u5bf6\u795a\u5ef6\u5ea5\u842c\u570b\u6b61\n<br>\u666f\u661f\u62f1\u6975\u4e94\u96f2\u7aef\n<br>\u6d77\u6ce2\u6f84\u78a7\u6625\u8f1d\u9e97 \n<br>\u65cc\u7bc0\u82b1\u9593\u96c6\u9cf3\u947e\n\n===Hanyu Pinyin===\nB\u01ceozu\u00f2 y\u00e1nxi\u016b w\u00e0ngu\u00f3 hu\u0101n\n<br>J\u01d0ngx\u012bng g\u01d2ngj\u00ed w\u01d4 y\u00fan du\u0101n\n<br>H\u01ceib\u014d ch\u00e9ngb\u00ec ch\u016bnhu\u012b l\u00ec\n<br>J\u012bngji\u00e9 hu\u0101ji\u0101n j\u00ed f\u00e8nglu\u00e1n\n\n===English Translation===\nTen thousand nations celebrate the [[Dragon Throne|Imperial throne]]'s prosperity\n<br>The fortune star climbs over the iridescent clouds of five colors\n<br>The [[East China Sea|crystal blue ocean]] glitters under spring's sunshine\n<br>Tributaries bow to the [[Emperor of China|Emperor]] like flowers centering a [[Phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]]\n<br>Ten thousand nations celebrate the imperial throne's prosperity\n<br>The fortune star climbs over the iridescent clouds of five colors\n<br>The crystal blue ocean glitters under spring's sunshine\n<br>Tributaries bow to the Emperor like flowers centering a phoenix\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Beiyang Fleet]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links ==\n\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fXpGpgYHj1k ''Anthem of the Beiyang Fleet'' on Youtube]\n\n[[Category:Military history of the Qing dynasty]]\n[[Category:Beiyang Fleet]]\n", "name_user": "Korean Jesus111", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEnglish Translation:deleted unecessary repeated text", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthem_of_the_Beiyang_Fleet"}
{"title_page": "Baba Gana Kingibe", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Baba Gana Kingibe\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| office1             = [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]]\n| president1          = [[Umaru Yar'Adua]]\n| term_start1         = July 2007\n| term_end1           = Sept 2008\n| predecessor1        = [[Ufot Ekaette]]\n| successor1          = [[Mahmud Yayale Ahmed]]\n| office2             = [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]]\n| president2          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start2         = 1997\n| term_end2           = 1998\n| predecessor2        = [[Bashir Dalhatu]]\n| successor2          = Bello Sulaiman\n| office3             = [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]]\n| president3          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start3         = 1995\n| term_end3           = 1997\n| predecessor3        = [[Alex Ibru]]\n| successor3          = [[Bashir Dalhatu]]\n| office4             = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)| Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| president4          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start4         = 1993\n| term_end4           = 1995\n| predecessor4        = [[Matthew Mbu]]\n| successor4          = [[Tom Ikimi]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1945|6|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[Borno State]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]\n| death_place         = \n| education           = [[Bishop's Stortford College]]\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Sussex]]\n| otherparty          = Peoples Front of Nigeria<br>(1988\u201389)<br>[[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]]<br> (1989\u20131993)<br>[[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Peoples Democractic Party]]<br>(1999\u20132015)\n| honorific_suffix    = [[Order of the Niger|GCON]]\n| party               = [[All Progressives Congress]]<br>(2015\u2013present)\n}}\n'''Baba Gana Kingibe''' [[Order of the Niger|GCON]] (born 25 June 1945)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=9EAOAQAAMAAJ&q=Baba+Gana+Kingibe+1945&dq=Baba+Gana+Kingibe+1945&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvjtvYsJLbAhVGsaQKHSBTDewQ6AEIRjAH Profile of Baba Gana Kingibe]</ref> is a Nigerian politician, diplomat and government official who served as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1993 to 1995, [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1995 to 1997, [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1997 to 1998; and [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]] from 2007 to 2008. \n\nIn [[1993 Nigerian presidential election]], he was the vice presidential candidate of the [[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]].\n\n==Early life==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nKingibe was born on 25 June 1945 to the family of Mustafa Shuwa and Ya Kingi Mallam. A [[Kanuri people|Kanuri]] from [[Borno State|Borno]], he grew up in [[Maiduguri]] and attended primary schools there. In 1958, he was admitted into the Borno Provincial Secondary School.   \n\nIn 1960, he left for the [[United Kingdom]] on a government scholarship to complete his [[GCE Ordinary Level|O'Level]] and [[A-level]] at [[Bishop's Stortford College]]. In 1965, he received his [[bachelor's degree]] in [[international relations]] from the [[University of Sussex]] (alongside [[Thabo Mbeki]]<ref name=\"Mbeki22\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c0kxegsps7IC&pg=PT187&dq=kingibe+sussex&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAGoVChMIqNLMjYzNxwIVATY-Ch13GwGT#v=onepage&q=kingibe%20sussex&f=false|title=A Legacy of Liberation: Thabo Mbeki and the Future of the South African Dream|date=2009|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>).  \n\n===Early career===\nIn 1965, he returned to Nigeria and was employed as a [[Research|researcher]] at [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]]. At the university, he became acquainted with the [[Kaduna Mafia]], a group of young western-educated [[intellectuals]], [[civil servants]] and [[Nigerian Armed Forces|military officers]] from [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamji.com/haruna/haruna304.htm|title=Ibrahim Tahir: An Appreciation|last=Daura|first=Mamman|date=|website=Gamji|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> During the [[Nigerian Civil War]], he became the head of features and current affairs at the Broadcasting Corporation of Northern Nigeria. \n\n==Diplomatic service==\nIn 1972, he joined the Nigerian Foreign Service where his first posting was the [[Nigerian High Commission in London]] as a senior political counsellor and later became the head of the political desk. \n\nFollowing the [[1976 Nigerian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]], Kingibe was seconded to the Supreme Military Headquarters (SMHQ) as the Principal Secretary, Political, from 1976 to 1979, where he was involved in the planning of the military's transfer of power programme, [[States of Nigeria|states creation]] and [[national delimitation]], [[Local government areas of Nigeria|local government reforms]] and the [[Constitution of Nigeria#1979 constitution (Second Republic)|constitutional drafting committee]] of the [[Second Nigerian Republic]].<ref>African Concord (1990). The New Helmsmen. Concord Press, Ikeja, Lagos. August 13, 1990</ref> In 1981, at the age of 36, he was appointed the Nigerian Ambassador to Greece, Cyprus and later Pakistan between 1981 and 1985. In 1986, Kingibe became a [[permanent secretary]] in the presidency of General [[Ibrahim Babangida]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blerf.org/index.php/biography/baba-gana-kingibe/|title=BABA, Gana Kingibe|last=Admin|date=2016-11-21|website=Biographical Legacy and Research Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n\nKingibe also served from October 2002 to September 2006 as the [[Special Envoy]] of the [[African Union]] to [[Sudan]] and subsequently Special Representative of the [[Chairperson of the African Union Commission]] and head of the [[African Union Mission in Sudan]].<ref name=\"GaM22\">[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-09-11-nigeria-president-exerts-authority-in-power-struggle \"Nigeria president exerts authority in power struggle\"] [[Mail & Guardian]] retrieved September 11, 2008</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Party politics===\nKingibe entered politics in the build up to the transition of the [[Third Nigerian Republic]]. In 1988, he was made director of organization of the People's Front of Nigeria which consisted of politicians such as [[Atiku Abubakar]], [[Bola Tinubu]], [[Abdullahi Aliyu Sumaila]] and [[Rabiu Kwankwaso]], which was then led by [[Shehu Musa Yar'Adua]]. \n\nThe front later joined with the [[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]] in 1989. During the conduct of elections for national executive positions in the party, Kingibe was sponsored by the People's Front faction of SDP as the party's chairman, a position he went on to clinch. As party chairman, Kingibe was involved in the organization of party's gubernatorial and presidential primaries in 1991 and 1992 respectively. \n\n=== 1993 presidential election ===\nHowever, after the cancellations of presidential elections in 1992 in which [[Shehu Musa Yar'Adua|Shehu Yar'Adua]] was a candidate, Kingibe put himself forward as a presidential candidate. He made a split from his initial camp, the PFN group and used his relationships with SDP state party chairmen to build his campaign. He lost the keenly contested primary conducted in Jos but after much prodding from SDP governors, he was selected by the primary winner, [[MKO Abiola]] as [[Vice-President of Nigeria|Vice-presidential]] running mate, creating a Muslim-Muslim ticket which was initially thought to be a deal breaker in the general elections. The pair won the electoral majority although the result was annulled by abdicating president General [[Ibrahim Babangida]].<ref name=\"Safari Books2\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cOVMBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA37&dq=kingibe++pfn&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMI7aCfjJ3exgIVAhmSCh3o7gtX#v=onepage&q=kingibe%20%20pfn&f=false/|title=Frank Kokori: The Struggle for June 12|date=2014|publisher=Safari Books|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Abacha administration ===\nKingibe later joined the Abacha administration as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1993 to 1995, [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1995 to 1997, and [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1997 to 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/335406-why-i-abandoned-june-12-joined-abacha-junta-kingibe.html|title=Why I abandoned June 12, joined Abacha junta - Kingibe - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2019-06-17|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary to the Government===\nIn June 2007, he was appointed [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]].<ref>Idowu Adelusi. Kingibe to move to Aso Rock Villa?. Nigerian Tribune, July 7, 2007.</ref> He was unceremoniously removed from office on September 8, 2008 by the President Umaru Yar'Adua,<ref name=\"GaM2\">[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-09-11-nigeria-president-exerts-authority-in-power-struggle \"Nigeria president exerts authority in power struggle\"] [[Mail & Guardian]] retrieved September 11, 2008</ref> after spreading rumors about the President's ill-health while believed to be contending for the presidency.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7604889.stm \"Nigerian leader appears in public\"] [[BBC News]]</ref>\n\n=== Buhari administration ===\nKingibe has been a powerful [[\u00c9minence grise|behind the scenes]] decision-maker in the Buhari administration, alongside chief of staff [[Abba Kyari (politician)|Abba Kyari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailycorrespondents.com.ng/2016/08/old-fox-baba-gana-kingibe-nigerias-defacto-prime-minister/|title=Old fox, Baba Gana Kingibe is Nigeria\u2019s defacto Prime Minister|last=Editor|date=2016-08-28|website=Daily Correspondents|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Country\n!Decoration\n!Presenter\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Nigeria]]\n|[[Order of the Niger|Grand Commander of the Order of the Niger]] (GCON); [[File:Ribbon bar of the Order of the Niger.gif|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ribbon%20bar%20of%20the%20Order%20of%20the%20Niger.gif|frameless|59x59px]]\n|[[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Muhammadu Buhari]]\n|Second highest national honour in Nigeria\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[http://www.cfr.org/bios/9885/baba_gana_kingibe.html Biography from the Council of Foreign Relations]\n\n{{Foreign Ministers of Nigeria}}\n{{Cabinet of President Umaru Yar'Adua}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingibe, Baba Gana}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Maiduguri]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Federal ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Nigeria to Greece]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Nigeria to Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Kanuri people]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Baba Gana Kingibe\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| office1             = [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]]\n| president1          = [[Umaru Yar'Adua]]\n| term_start1         = July 2007\n| term_end1           = Sept 2008\n| predecessor1        = [[Ufot Ekaette]]\n| successor1          = [[Mahmud Yayale Ahmed]]\n| office2             = [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]]\n| president2          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start2         = 1997\n| term_end2           = 1998\n| predecessor2        = [[Bashir Dalhatu]]\n| successor2          = Bello Sulaiman\n| office3             = [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]]\n| president3          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start3         = 1995\n| term_end3           = 1997\n| predecessor3        = [[Alex Ibru]]\n| successor3          = [[Bashir Dalhatu]]\n| office4             = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)| Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| president4          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| term_start4         = 1993\n| term_end4           = 1995\n| predecessor4        = [[Matthew Mbu]]\n| successor4          = [[Tom Ikimi]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1945|6|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[Borno State]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]\n| death_place         = \n| education           = [[Bishop's Stortford College]]\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Sussex]]\n| otherparty          = Peoples Front of Nigeria<br>(1988\u201389)<br>[[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]]<br> (1989\u20131993)<br>[[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Peoples Democractic Party]]<br>(1999\u20132015)\n| honorific_suffix    = [[Order of the Niger|GCON]]\n| party               = [[All Progressives Congress]]<br>(2015\u2013present)\n}}\n'''Baba Gana Kingibe''' [[Order of the Niger|GCON]] (born 25 June 1945)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=9EAOAQAAMAAJ&q=Baba+Gana+Kingibe+1945&dq=Baba+Gana+Kingibe+1945&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvjtvYsJLbAhVGsaQKHSBTDewQ6AEIRjAH Profile of Baba Gana Kingibe]</ref> is a Nigerian politician, diplomat and government official who served as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1993 to 1995, [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1995 to 1997, [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1997 to 1998; and [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]] from 2007 to 2008. \n\nIn [[1993 Nigerian presidential election]], he was the vice presidential candidate of the [[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]].\n\n==Early life==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\nKingibe was born on 25 June 1945 to the family of Mustafa Shuwa and Ya Kingi Mallam. A [[Kanuri people|Kanuri]] from [[Borno State|Borno]], he grew up in [[Maiduguri]] and attended primary schools there. In 1958, he was admitted into the Borno Provincial Secondary School.   \n\nIn 1960, he left for the [[United Kingdom]] on a government scholarship to complete his [[GCE Ordinary Level|O'Level]] and [[A-level]] at [[Bishop's Stortford College]]. In 1965, he received his [[bachelor's degree]] in [[international relations]] from the [[University of Sussex]] (alongside [[Thabo Mbeki]]<ref name=\"Mbeki22\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c0kxegsps7IC&pg=PT187&dq=kingibe+sussex&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAGoVChMIqNLMjYzNxwIVATY-Ch13GwGT#v=onepage&q=kingibe%20sussex&f=false|title=A Legacy of Liberation: Thabo Mbeki and the Future of the South African Dream|date=2009|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>).  \n\n===Early career===\nIn 1965, he returned to Nigeria and was employed as a [[Research|researcher]] at [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]]. At the university, he became acquainted with the [[Kaduna Mafia]], a group of young western-educated [[intellectuals]], [[civil servants]] and [[Nigerian Armed Forces|military officers]] from [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamji.com/haruna/haruna304.htm|title=Ibrahim Tahir: An Appreciation|last=Daura|first=Mamman|date=|website=Gamji|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> During the [[Nigerian Civil War]], he became the head of features and current affairs at the Broadcasting Corporation of Northern Nigeria. \n\n==Diplomatic service==\nIn 1972, he joined the Nigerian Foreign Service where his first posting was the [[Nigerian High Commission in London]] as a senior political counsellor and later became the head of the political desk. \n\nFollowing the [[1976 Nigerian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]], Kingibe was seconded to the Supreme Military Headquarters (SMHQ) as the Principal Secretary, Political, from 1976 to 1979, where he was involved in the planning of the military's transfer of power programme, [[States of Nigeria|states creation]] and [[national delimitation]], [[Local government areas of Nigeria|local government reforms]] and the [[Constitution of Nigeria#1979 constitution (Second Republic)|constitutional drafting committee]] of the [[Second Nigerian Republic]].<ref>African Concord (1990). The New Helmsmen. Concord Press, Ikeja, Lagos. August 13, 1990</ref> In 1981, at the age of 36, he was appointed the Nigerian Ambassador to Greece, Cyprus and later Pakistan between 1981 and 1985. In 1986, Kingibe became a [[permanent secretary]] in the presidency of General [[Ibrahim Babangida]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blerf.org/index.php/biography/baba-gana-kingibe/|title=BABA, Gana Kingibe|last=Admin|date=2016-11-21|website=Biographical Legacy and Research Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n\nKingibe also served from October 2002 to September 2006 as the [[Special Envoy]] of the [[African Union]] to [[Sudan]] and subsequently Special Representative of the [[Chairperson of the African Union Commission]] and head of the [[African Union Mission in Sudan]] (AMIS) and Darfur.<ref name=\"GaM22\">[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-09-11-nigeria-president-exerts-authority-in-power-struggle \"Nigeria president exerts authority in power struggle\"] [[Mail & Guardian]] retrieved September 11, 2008</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Party politics===\nKingibe entered politics in the build up to the transition of the [[Third Nigerian Republic]]. In 1988, he was made director of organization of the People's Front of Nigeria which consisted of politicians such as [[Atiku Abubakar]], [[Bola Tinubu]], [[Abdullahi Aliyu Sumaila]] and [[Rabiu Kwankwaso]], which was then led by [[Shehu Musa Yar'Adua]]. \n\nThe front later joined with the [[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]] in 1989. During the conduct of elections for national executive positions in the party, Kingibe was sponsored by the People's Front faction of SDP as the party's chairman, a position he went on to clinch. As party chairman, Kingibe was involved in the organization of party's gubernatorial and presidential primaries in 1991 and 1992 respectively. \n\n=== 1993 presidential election ===\nHowever, after the cancellations of presidential elections in 1992 in which [[Shehu Musa Yar'Adua|Shehu Yar'Adua]] was a candidate, Kingibe put himself forward as a presidential candidate. He made a split from his initial camp, the PFN group and used his relationships with SDP state party chairmen to build his campaign. He lost the keenly contested primary conducted in Jos but after much prodding from SDP governors, he was selected by the primary winner, [[MKO Abiola]] as [[Vice-President of Nigeria|Vice-presidential]] running mate, creating a Muslim-Muslim ticket which was initially thought to be a deal breaker in the general elections. The pair won the electoral majority although the result was annulled by abdicating president General [[Ibrahim Babangida]].<ref name=\"Safari Books2\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cOVMBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA37&dq=kingibe++pfn&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMI7aCfjJ3exgIVAhmSCh3o7gtX#v=onepage&q=kingibe%20%20pfn&f=false/|title=Frank Kokori: The Struggle for June 12|date=2014|publisher=Safari Books|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Abacha administration ===\nKingibe later joined the Abacha administration as [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Nigeria)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] from 1993 to 1995, [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1995 to 1997, and [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1997 to 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/335406-why-i-abandoned-june-12-joined-abacha-junta-kingibe.html|title=Why I abandoned June 12, joined Abacha junta - Kingibe - Premium Times Nigeria|date=2019-06-17|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary to the Government===\nIn June 2007, he was appointed [[Secretary to the Government of the Federation]].<ref>Idowu Adelusi. Kingibe to move to Aso Rock Villa?. Nigerian Tribune, July 7, 2007.</ref> He was unceremoniously removed from office on September 8, 2008 by the President Umaru Yar'Adua,<ref name=\"GaM2\">[http://www.mg.co.za/article/2008-09-11-nigeria-president-exerts-authority-in-power-struggle \"Nigeria president exerts authority in power struggle\"] [[Mail & Guardian]] retrieved September 11, 2008</ref> after spreading rumors about the President's ill-health while believed to be contending for the presidency.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7604889.stm \"Nigerian leader appears in public\"] [[BBC News]]</ref>\n\n=== Buhari administration ===\nKingibe has been a powerful [[\u00c9minence grise|behind the scenes]] decision-maker in the Buhari administration, alongside chief of staff [[Abba Kyari (politician)|Abba Kyari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailycorrespondents.com.ng/2016/08/old-fox-baba-gana-kingibe-nigerias-defacto-prime-minister/|title=Old fox, Baba Gana Kingibe is Nigeria\u2019s defacto Prime Minister|last=Editor|date=2016-08-28|website=Daily Correspondents|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Country\n!Decoration\n!Presenter\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Nigeria]]\n|[[Order of the Niger|Grand Commander of the Order of the Niger]] (GCON); [[File:Ribbon bar of the Order of the Niger.gif|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ribbon%20bar%20of%20the%20Order%20of%20the%20Niger.gif|frameless|59x59px]]\n|[[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Muhammadu Buhari]]\n|Second highest national honour in Nigeria\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[http://www.cfr.org/bios/9885/baba_gana_kingibe.html Biography from the Council of Foreign Relations]\n\n{{Foreign Ministers of Nigeria}}\n{{Cabinet of President Umaru Yar'Adua}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingibe, Baba Gana}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Maiduguri]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Federal ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Nigeria to Greece]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of Nigeria to Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Kanuri people]]\n", "name_user": "Zerzuran", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDiplomatic service", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baba_Gana_Kingibe"}
{"title_page": "Hindi in Bihar", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n[[Hindi]] is one of the official languages of [[Bihar]], whilst the majority of the people speak one of the [[Bihari languages]]..\n\n==Hindi journalism==\n''Biharbandhu'' was the first [[Hindi]] [https://mintsofindia.com/bihar-news-in-hindi/ newspaper published from Bihar]. It was started in 1872 by Keshav Ram Bhatta, a [[Marathi people|Maharashtrian]] [[Brahman]] settled in [[Bihar-E-Sharif|Biharsharif]].<ref name=\"journalism\">Ahmad Qeyamuddin, ''Patna Through the ages: Glimpses of History, Society and Economy, Commonwealth Publishers'', New Delhi, 1988</ref> [[Hindi]] [[journalism]] in Bihar, and specially [[Patna]], could make little headway initially. It was mainly due to lack of respect for [[Hindi]] among the people at large. Many [[Hindi]] journals took birth and after a lapse of time vanished. Many journals were shelved even in the [[embryo]].<ref>Rajendra Abhinandan Granth, ''\"Nagri Pracharini Sabha\"'', Arrah, 3 March 1950, p. 353</ref> But once [[Hindi]] enlisted the [[official]] support, it started making a dent into the [[Extreme points of Earth#Remoteness|remote]] areas in Bihar. [[Hindi]] [[journalism]] also acquired wisdom and maturity and its longevity was prolonged. [[Hindi]] was introduced in the law courts in Bihar in 1880.<ref>Kumar N., ''Journalism in Bihar'', A Supplement to Bihar State Gazette pp. 28</ref><ref name=\"journalism\"/>\n\n==20th-century publications==\nThe beginning of the twentieth century was marked by a number of notable new publications. A monthly magazine named ''Bharat Ratna'' was started from [[Patna]] in 1901. It was followed by ''Kshtriya Hitaishi'', ''Aryavarta'' from Dinapure, [[Patna]], ''Udyoga'' and ''Chaitanya Chandrika''.<ref>''Bihar ki Sahityik Pragati'', Bihar Hindi Sahitya Sammelan, Patna 1956, pp. 73</ref> ''Udyog'' was edited by Vijyaanand Tripathy, a famous poet of the time and ''Chaitanya Chandrika'' by Krishna Chaitanya Goswami, a literary figures of that time. This literary activities were not confined to [[Patna]] alone but to many districts of Bihar.<ref>''Jayanti Smarak Granth'', pp. 583-585</ref><ref name=\"journalism\"/>\n\n==Constitutional issues==\nDespite the large number of speakers of [[Bihari languages]], these languages, except Maithili (which is recognised under the [[Eighth Schedule of the Constitution of India]]), have not been constitutionally recognised in [[India]]. [[Hindi]] is the language used for educational and official matters in Bihar, with English occasionally used in education and government.<ref>[http://www.diehardindian.com/demogrph/moredemo/histlang.htm History of Indian languages] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226234832/http://www.diehardindian.com/demogrph/moredemo/histlang.htm |date=2012-02-26 }},\"Bihari is actually the name of a group of two related languages\u2014Bhojpuri,  and Magahi\u2014spoken mainly in northeastern India in Bihar. Despite its large number of speakers, Bihari is not a constitutionally recognised language of India. Even in Bihar, Hindi is the language used for educational and official matters.\"</ref> These languages was legally absorbed under the subordinate label of [[Hindi|HINDI]] in the 1961 Census. Such state and national politics are creating conditions for language endangerments.<ref>{{cite conference\n  | last = Verma\n  | first = Mahandra K.\n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Language Endangerment and Indian languages : An exploration and a critique\n  | booktitle = Linguistic Structure and Language Dynamics in South Asia\n  | place = \n  | date = \n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=tcfJY7kANo8C&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=awadhi+and+magahi+languages&source=web&ots=CXhEbrAUH5&sig=e3GeSyfuGmTbRXtRK-vT100cFAQ&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=10&ct=result#PPA3,M1\n  | accessdate =  }}</ref>\n\n==Struggle between languages==\nThe first success for spreading [[Hindi]] occurred in Bihar in 1881, when [[Hindi]] displaced [[Urdu]] as the sole official language of the [[province]]. In this struggle between competing [[Hindi]] and [[Urdu]], the potential claims of the three large mother tongues in the region - [[Magahi]], [[Bhojpuri]] and [[Maithili language|Maithili]] were ignored. After independence [[Hindi]] was again given the sole official status through the Bihar Official Language Act, 1950. <ref> Brass Paul R., ''The Politics of India Since Independence'', Cambridge University Press, pp. 183</ref> [[Urdu]] became the second official language in the undivided State of Bihar on 16 August 1989.\n\n[[Maithili language|Maithili]] has been the only one among the [[Bihari languages]], which has been trying to constantly deny superimposition of [[Hindi]] over its identity. The other two ([[Bhojpuri]] and [[Magahi]]) have given up their claims and have resigned to accept the status of dialects of [[Hindi]].{{cn|date=October 2019}} Maithili was officially recognised by the government of India in 2003, after an active movement led by [[Maithili language|Maithili]] speakers.\n\n==Statistics==\nThe number of speakers of [[Bihari languages]] are difficult to indicate because of unreliable sources. In the urban region most educated speakers of the language name [[Hindi]] as their language because this is what they use in formal contexts and believe it to be the appropriate response because of unawareness. The uneducated and the rural population of the region return [[Hindi]] as the generic name for their language. <ref name= \"Dhanesh\" >Jain Dhanesh, Cardona George, The Indo-Aryan Languages, pp500, \"..the number of speakers of Bihari languages are difficult to indicate because of unreliable sources. In the urban region most educated speakers of the language name Hindi as their language because this is what they use in formal contexts and believe it to be the appropriate response because of unawareness. The uneducated and the rural population of the region return Hindi as the generic name for their language.\"</ref>\n\n==References and footnotes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n[[Category:Culture of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Hindi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n[[Hindi]] is one of the official languages of [[Bihar]], whilst the majority of the people speak one of the [[Bihari languages]]..\n\n==Hindi journalism==\n''Biharbandhu'' was the first [[Hindi]] newspaper published from Bihar. It was started in 1872 by Keshav Ram Bhatta, a [[Marathi people|Maharashtrian]] [[Brahman]] settled in [[Bihar-E-Sharif|Biharsharif]].<ref name=\"journalism\">Ahmad Qeyamuddin, ''Patna Through the ages: Glimpses of History, Society and Economy, Commonwealth Publishers'', New Delhi, 1988</ref> [[Hindi]] [[journalism]] in Bihar, and specially [[Patna]], could make little headway initially. It was mainly due to lack of respect for [[Hindi]] among the people at large. Many [[Hindi]] journals took birth and after a lapse of time vanished. Many journals were shelved even in the [[embryo]].<ref>Rajendra Abhinandan Granth, ''\"Nagri Pracharini Sabha\"'', Arrah, 3 March 1950, p. 353</ref> But once [[Hindi]] enlisted the [[official]] support, it started making a dent into the [[Extreme points of Earth#Remoteness|remote]] areas in Bihar. [[Hindi]] [[journalism]] also acquired wisdom and maturity and its longevity was prolonged. [[Hindi]] was introduced in the law courts in Bihar in 1880.<ref>Kumar N., ''Journalism in Bihar'', A Supplement to Bihar State Gazette pp. 28</ref><ref name=\"journalism\"/>\n\n==20th-century publications==\nThe beginning of the twentieth century was marked by a number of notable new publications. A monthly magazine named ''Bharat Ratna'' was started from [[Patna]] in 1901. It was followed by ''Kshtriya Hitaishi'', ''Aryavarta'' from Dinapure, [[Patna]], ''Udyoga'' and ''Chaitanya Chandrika''.<ref>''Bihar ki Sahityik Pragati'', Bihar Hindi Sahitya Sammelan, Patna 1956, pp. 73</ref> ''Udyog'' was edited by Vijyaanand Tripathy, a famous poet of the time and ''Chaitanya Chandrika'' by Krishna Chaitanya Goswami, a literary figures of that time. This literary activities were not confined to [[Patna]] alone but to many districts of Bihar.<ref>''Jayanti Smarak Granth'', pp. 583-585</ref><ref name=\"journalism\"/>\n\n==Constitutional issues==\nDespite the large number of speakers of [[Bihari languages]], these languages, except Maithili (which is recognised under the [[Eighth Schedule of the Constitution of India]]), have not been constitutionally recognised in [[India]]. [[Hindi]] is the language used for educational and official matters in Bihar, with English occasionally used in education and government.<ref>[http://www.diehardindian.com/demogrph/moredemo/histlang.htm History of Indian languages] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226234832/http://www.diehardindian.com/demogrph/moredemo/histlang.htm |date=2012-02-26 }},\"Bihari is actually the name of a group of two related languages\u2014Bhojpuri,  and Magahi\u2014spoken mainly in northeastern India in Bihar. Despite its large number of speakers, Bihari is not a constitutionally recognised language of India. Even in Bihar, Hindi is the language used for educational and official matters.\"</ref> These languages was legally absorbed under the subordinate label of [[Hindi|HINDI]] in the 1961 Census. Such state and national politics are creating conditions for language endangerments.<ref>{{cite conference\n  | last = Verma\n  | first = Mahandra K.\n  | coauthors = \n  | title = Language Endangerment and Indian languages : An exploration and a critique\n  | booktitle = Linguistic Structure and Language Dynamics in South Asia\n  | place = \n  | date = \n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=tcfJY7kANo8C&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=awadhi+and+magahi+languages&source=web&ots=CXhEbrAUH5&sig=e3GeSyfuGmTbRXtRK-vT100cFAQ&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=10&ct=result#PPA3,M1\n  | accessdate =  }}</ref>\n\n==Struggle between languages==\nThe first success for spreading [[Hindi]] occurred in Bihar in 1881, when [[Hindi]] displaced [[Urdu]] as the sole official language of the [[province]]. In this struggle between competing [[Hindi]] and [[Urdu]], the potential claims of the three large mother tongues in the region - [[Magahi]], [[Bhojpuri]] and [[Maithili language|Maithili]] were ignored. After independence [[Hindi]] was again given the sole official status through the Bihar Official Language Act, 1950. <ref> Brass Paul R., ''The Politics of India Since Independence'', Cambridge University Press, pp. 183</ref> [[Urdu]] became the second official language in the undivided State of Bihar on 16 August 1989.\n\n[[Maithili language|Maithili]] has been the only one among the [[Bihari languages]], which has been trying to constantly deny superimposition of [[Hindi]] over its identity. The other two ([[Bhojpuri]] and [[Magahi]]) have given up their claims and have resigned to accept the status of dialects of [[Hindi]].{{cn|date=October 2019}} Maithili was officially recognised by the government of India in 2003, after an active movement led by [[Maithili language|Maithili]] speakers.\n\n==Statistics==\nThe number of speakers of [[Bihari languages]] are difficult to indicate because of unreliable sources. In the urban region most educated speakers of the language name [[Hindi]] as their language because this is what they use in formal contexts and believe it to be the appropriate response because of unawareness. The uneducated and the rural population of the region return [[Hindi]] as the generic name for their language. <ref name= \"Dhanesh\" >Jain Dhanesh, Cardona George, The Indo-Aryan Languages, pp500, \"..the number of speakers of Bihari languages are difficult to indicate because of unreliable sources. In the urban region most educated speakers of the language name Hindi as their language because this is what they use in formal contexts and believe it to be the appropriate response because of unawareness. The uneducated and the rural population of the region return Hindi as the generic name for their language.\"</ref>\n\n==References and footnotes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n[[Category:Culture of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Hindi]]\n", "name_user": "2402:8100:3a03:8623:fd29:8574:fdc8:d978", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHindi journalism)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindi_in_Bihar"}
